Supervised Learning Capstone: RoboZZle¶

Jared Pollack¶

April 22, 2020¶

Introduction¶

What is RoboZZle?¶

  • RoboZZle = Robot + Puzzle
  • video game available at robozzle.com, xBox ('Rob'), Android ('RoboZZle Droid')
  • player programs a robot to pick up stars, which solves the puzzle
  • all puzzles are designed by the players

Gameplay and Features¶

  • red, green, and blue tiles, or empty cells on a 16 x 12 grid
  • functions and command slots
  • commands: Forward, Left, Right, function calls
  • paint & conditions

Why RoboZZle¶

  • I am both a player and designer
  • it's why I started coding, which put me on the data science path
  • Robozzle website maintains player and puzzle statistics
  • process of solving puzzles has applications to reinforcement learning

Finding a Target Variable¶

  • players can vote on puzzles they solve
  • 'Like' / 'Dislike' system similar to YouTube's 'thumbs-up' / 'thumbs-down' for videos
  • outcomes and assigned values: Like = 1, Dislike = -1, Non-Vote = 0
  • target variable: popularity

Research Goals:¶

  1. Determine the factors that influence the popularity of Robozzle puzzles
  2. Construct models to predict a puzzle's popularity based on these factors (variables).

2. Collecting Data¶

  • web-scraping required (no known RoboZZle data sets)
  • 1st scrape (html): puzzle ID, title, author, date posted, players solved, liked/disliked, difficulty, solution lengths
  • 2nd scrape (JavaScript): tiles, functions, command slots, stars, paint
  • store data in python dictionaries; convert to DataFrames
  • final count: 8,603 puzzles

Data Overview¶

Numeric Variables¶

  • puzzleid (int)
  • difficulty (float) : 1 (easy) - 5 (hard)
  • players_solved (int)
  • solution lengths (int) : variables for mean (float), min (int), and mode (int); multimodal = 0
  • likes (int)
  • dislikes (int)
  • functions (int) : 1 - 5
  • commands (int) : 1 - 50
  • paint (int/bool) : yes = 1; no = 0
  • number of red, green, blue tiles (int)
  • stars (int)

Categorical and Datetime Variables¶

  • Categorical: title, author
  • Datetime: date posted

title: may affect popularity; but dropped assuming author will be a stronger feature.

author: utilize dummy variables

date posted: convert to day posted (set 1st puzzle at day 1, and all others relative)

    x = robozzle.year[i]
    ytd = 365 * x 
    if robozzle.year[i] > 4:
        ytd += 1
    if robozzle.year[i] > 8:
        ytd += 1
    robozzle.yearindays[i] = ytd

for i in range(0, 8603):
    x = robozzle.month[i]
    days = 0
    if x > 1:
        days = 31
    if x > 2:
        if robozzle.year[i] % 4 == 0:
            days += 29
        else:
            days += 28
    if x > 3:
        days += 31
    if x > 4:
        days += 30
    if x > 5:
        days += 31
    if x > 6:
        days += 30
    if x > 7:
        days += 31
    if x > 8:
        days += 31
    if x > 9:
        days += 30
    if x > 10:
        days += 31
    if x > 11:
        days += 30
    robozzle.monthindays[i] = days

for i in range(0, 8603):
    robozzle['day_posted'][i] = robozzle.yearindays[i] + robozzle.monthindays[i] + robozzle.day[i]

robozzle.drop(['date_posted', 'title', 'year', 'month', 'day',
               'yearindays', 'monthindays', 'day_posted'], 1, inplace=True)

Quick Note on RoboZZle¶

  • RoboZZle launched over a decade ago
  • initially popular, but interest has faded
  • statistically speaking, players solved decreases with time (see plot below)
  • smaller sample sizes result in greater variance
  • expect models to perform better as players solved increases

4. Research Questions¶

Given the available statistics, how well can we:

  1. Explain the variance in the popularity of RoboZZle puzzles?
  2. Predict the popularity of a RoboZZle puzzle?

  • familiarity with RoboZZle data (domain knowledge) proves helpful

Popularity Formulas and Distributions¶

  • construct the formulas to represent popularity
  • evaluate their distributions for normality and check for outliers
  • apply transformations or treat outliers as needed

Formulas:¶

  1. popularity = (likes - dislikes) / players solved

  2. popularity = Yeo-Johnson-transformed((likes - dislikes) / players solved)

Categorical Distributions¶

Author¶

  • over 1,500 authors account for 8,600 puzzles
  • impractical to create 1,500 dummy variables
  • assign a value of 'other' to authors with fewer than n puzzles submitted
  • test on range of values to determine an optimum threshold
  • distribution will depend on threshold

Strange Correlations?¶

  1. blue tiles more highly correlated with other variables than red and green... why?

Tradition! Designers usually use blue tiles as the main path for the robot, and use red and green tiles to signal turns.

  1. correlation between mean solution length and commands... should it be stronger?

Inexperienced authors often submit puzzles with all 50 command slots available, when only a few are needed to solve the puzzle.

Formal Hypothesis Test¶

  • choose a variable to determine if it has any explanatory power for the target
  • Plot regression line for min_sol_len vs. popularity

6. Models¶

Preliminary Tests¶

  1. determine an upper limit on players_solved
  2. find the optimum threshold for author counts
  3. choose popularity metric for modeling

1. Upper Limit on players_solved¶

  • used linear regression to test 5 thresholds: players_solved < 14,500; 10,000; 5,000; 2,000; 1,000
  • while loop with each test threshold along with increasing lower threshold starting with players_solved > 0
  • loop terminates when lower threshold filters more than half of data set

Here is a snippet:

i = 0
frac_dataset = 1
while frac_dataset > 0.5:
    rob_std = robozzle[(robozzle.players_solved > i) & (robozzle.players_solved < 14500)]
    frac_dataset = len(X)/8603
    i += 1
  • averaged mean squared error results
  • lowest average MSE: players_solved < 14,500 (will be used for modeling)
  • complete code omitted due to time constraints

2. Optimum Threshold for author counts¶

  • used linear regression to test thresholds from 100 down to 6
  • nested loop to vary players_solved lower threshold

As the threshold increases, R-squared decreases, and MSE increases. The threshold will be set at 6, producing 212 dummy variables.

Lowering the threshold further would cause rapid expansion of the feature set.

author_counts = robozzle.author.value_counts()
i = 7
while i > 0:
    num_dummies = len(author_counts[author_counts >= i])
    print('Setting the threshold at {} would result in {} dummy variables.'.format(i, num_dummies))
    i -= 1

Setting the threshold at 7 would result in 156 dummy variables.
Setting the threshold at 6 would result in 212 dummy variables.
Setting the threshold at 5 would result in 356 dummy variables.
Setting the threshold at 4 would result in 454 dummy variables.
Setting the threshold at 3 would result in 576 dummy variables.
Setting the threshold at 2 would result in 830 dummy variables.
Setting the threshold at 1 would result in 1516 dummy variables.

  • python dictionaries capture scores and are converted to DataFrames for analysis

Mean Squared Error¶

  • most important regression metric (squared difference between observed and predicted values)
  • lower is better
  • Nu Support Vector Regression: worst performer, long time to process
  • Bayesian Ridge - Linear and Ridge models overlapping (removed for clarity)
  • Gradient Boosting - 2nd best model (with GridSearchCV nearly identical)

  • Random Forest with RandomizedSearchCV slightly outperformed standard RF (not shown)

  • all models show consistent improvement as the players solved threshold increases, demonstrating the effect of sample size on predictability

R-Squared¶

  • proportion of variance in target variable predictable from features
  • higher is better
  • NuSVR again the worst model; showed decreasing scores when other models were steady
  • Bayesian Ridge, Linear and Ridge: performance almost identical to one another
  • Gradient Boost (standard and with GridSearchCV) again 2nd best model type

  • Random Forests produce highest scores

  • all models show sharp improvement as players solved threshold increases from 2 to about 10

  • while proportion of explainable variance (R-squared) flattens around 15, MSE shows that prediction accuracy continues to improve

7. Conclusion¶

  • RoboZZle more popular 11 years ago
  • analysis of a niche game can still provide insights
  • popularity prediction models utilized by YouTube; applicable to any entity or platform that captures user enjoyment
  • comparing RoboZZle to YouTube: some metrics apply, others don't; highlights importance of collecting data that "tells the whole story"
  • any company interested in the public's reception of product or service would benefit from reliable methods of estimating popularity
